   =20
 =20
Sometimes banks get in trouble with regulators for misconduct, and the regu=
lators fine the banks and issue an order describing=C2=A0the misconduct, an=
d I read a description of the misconduct and am like =E2=80=9Cah yes that s=
ounds like misconduct.=E2=80=9D Other times, I read the description and am=
=C2=A0like =E2=80=9Chmm I guess but that=E2=80=99s kind of a gray area and =
I can understand why they thought it was allowed.=E2=80=9D (Perhaps this is=
 just me.) But sometimes, I read the description of the misconduct and am=
=C2=A0like =E2=80=9Cwell that=E2=80=99s just=C2=A0using a computer, that=E2=
=80=99s just how computers work, anyone would mess that up,=C2=A0you=C2=A0c=
an=E2=80=99t blame them for that.=E2=80=9D Of course there the misconduct i=
s in=C2=A0designing=C2=A0the computer system in such a way that people will=
 inevitably mess it up.For some reason, that=C2=A0sort of misconduct seems =
to happen a lot at Citigroup Inc. In 2021, Citi accidentally sent $900 mill=
ion to some angry hedge funds because of what I called =E2=80=9Ca gothic ho=
rror story about software design.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Today the UK=E2=80=99s Fina=
ncial Conduct Authority and Prudential Regulatory Authority fined Citi =C2=
=A361.6 million ($79 million) for a 2022 fat-finger stock trade that happen=
ed like this:On the morning of 2 May 2022 (a UK Bank Holiday), a trader on =
the Delta 1 Desk made an inputting error whilst loading a basket of equitie=
s into an Order Management System (OMS) used by the Delta 1 Desk, called PT=
E. The trader had=C2=A0intended to sell a basket of equities to the value U=
