adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Oops</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes banks get in trouble with re=
gulators for misconduct, and the regulators fine the banks and issue an ord=
er describing=C2=A0the misconduct, and I read a description of the miscondu=
ct and am like =E2=80=9Cah yes that sounds like misconduct.=E2=80=9D Other =
times, I read the description and am=C2=A0like =E2=80=9Chmm I guess but tha=
t=E2=80=99s kind of a gray area and I can understand why they thought it wa=
s allowed.=E2=80=9D (Perhaps this is just me.) But sometimes, I read the de=
scription of the misconduct and am=C2=A0like =E2=80=9Cwell that=E2=80=99s j=
ust=C2=A0using a computer, that=E2=80=99s just how computers work, anyone w=
ould mess that up,=C2=A0you=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t blame them for that.=E2=80=
=9D Of course there the misconduct is in=C2=A0<em>designing=C2=A0</em>the c=
omputer system in such a way that people will inevitably mess it up.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For some reason, that=C2=A0sort of misconduct see=
ms to happen a lot at Citigroup Inc. In 2021, Citi accidentally sent $900 m=
illion to some angry hedge funds because of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/35465286.256336/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMTcvY2l0aS1jYW4tdC1oYXZlLWl0cy05MDAtbWls=
bGlvbi1iYWNrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjIyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXR=
tX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDUyMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdH=
VmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB715431d0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">what I called</a> =E2=80=9C=
a gothic horror story about software design.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Today the UK=E2=
=80=99s Financial Conduct Authority and Prudential Regulatory Authority <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35465286.256336/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDUtMjIvY2l0aWdyb3Vw=
LWZpbmVkLTYxLTYtbWlsbGlvbi1vdmVyLWZhdC1maW5nZXItdHJhZGluZy1ibHVuZGVyP2NtcGl=
kPUJCRDA1MjIyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbG=
V0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDUyMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBb455fde9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">fined Citi =C2=A361.6 million</a> ($79 millio=
n) for a 2022 fat-finger stock trade that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/35465286.256336/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmNhLm9yZy51ay9wdWJ=
saWNhdGlvbi9maW5hbC1ub3RpY2VzL2NpdGlncm91cC1nbG9iYWwtbWFya2V0cy1saW1pdGVkLT=
IwMjQucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeaf13b9d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">happened like this</a=
>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the morning of 2 May 2022=
 (a UK Bank Holiday), a trader on the Delta 1 Desk made an inputting error =
whilst loading a basket of equities into an Order Management System (OMS) u=
sed by the Delta 1 Desk, called PTE. The trader had=C2=A0intended to sell a=
 basket of equities to the value US$58m. However, the trader erroneously lo=
aded a basket with a notional size of US$444bn comprising 349 stocks, acros=
s multiple European markets. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The =
trader had entered the value of the basket of equities in the wrong field, =
the unit quantity field rather than the notional value field, whilst enteri=
ng the instructions which created the erroneous basket.</p></blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is=C2=A0from <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/35465286.256336/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmFua29mZW5nbGFuZ=
C5jby51ay8tL21lZGlhL2JvZS9maWxlcy9wcnVkZW50aWFsLXJlZ3VsYXRpb24vcmVndWxhdG9y=
eS1hY3Rpb24vZmluYWwtbm90aWNlLWZyb20tYm9lLWFuZC1wcmEtdG8tY2l0aWdyb3VwLWdsb2J=
hbC1tYXJrZXRzLWxpbWl0ZWQucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB29f8195e" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
the FCA=E2=80=99s order</a>; here are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/35465286.256336/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmNhLm9yZy51ay9uZXdzL3B=
yZXNzLXJlbGVhc2VzL2ZjYS1maW5lcy1jZ21sLTI3LW1pbGxpb24/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB0d3a7c05" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">the announcement</a> and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/35465286.256336/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmFua29mZW5nbGF=
uZC5jby51ay8tL21lZGlhL2JvZS9maWxlcy9wcnVkZW50aWFsLXJlZ3VsYXRpb24vcmVndWxhdG=
9yeS1hY3Rpb24vZmluYWwtbm90aWNlLWZyb20tYm9lLWFuZC1wcmEtdG8tY2l0aWdyb3VwLWdsb=
2JhbC1tYXJrZXRzLWxpbWl0ZWQucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC29f8195e" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
the PRA order</a>, which actually goes through a number of previous Citigro=
up computer errors. But this May 2022 incident is the big one.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, the story is that the trader worked on the delta=
-one desk, trading equity index futures. Citi got a client order to sell a =
block of MSCI World Index futures, and the trader =E2=80=9Cset about bookin=
g a basket of equities to hedge a proportion of CGML=E2=80=99s European exp=
osure to the MSCI World Index.=E2=80=9D This meant selling a lot of individ=
ual stocks:=C2=A0Citi=E2=80=99s computer had =E2=80=9Ca pre-loaded index=E2=
=80=9D reflecting 349 stocks =E2=80=9Cacross 13 European countries=E2=80=9D=
 that the trader wanted to sell to hedge.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">S=
o there=E2=80=99s a computer=C2=A0screen with=C2=A0a box for =E2=80=9Chow m=
any shares do you want to sell=E2=80=9D (or, rather, units of the basket)=
=C2=A0and another box for =E2=80=9Chow many dollars worth do you want to se=
ll,=E2=80=9D and you can input your trade either way. If the units of the b=
asket have a notional value of $7,684 each, you can type =E2=80=9C7,548=E2=
=80=9D in the =E2=80=9Cunits=E2=80=9D field, or you can type =E2=80=9C58,00=
0,000=E2=80=9D in the =E2=80=9Cdollars=E2=80=9D field, and either way you w=
ill sell about 7,548 units for about $58 million.<a class=3D"footnote-index=
" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display=
: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if instead you type =E2=80=9C58,00=
0,000=E2=80=9D in the units field, you will sell 58 million units for $444 =
billion. And that will be extremely bad, because you did not mean to do tha=
t, and selling $444 billion of stock all at once is going to crash the mark=
et.=C2=A0So you will try very hard not to type your order in the wrong box.=
 Most days, you will succeed. In fact, the chances are good that you will g=
o your whole career as a trader at Citigroup without ever typing a big orde=
r in the wrong box. But will=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>Citi trader=C2=A0<em>on=
ce=C2=A0</em>type a big order in the wrong box? With a large enough sample,=
 yes, of course. This one did.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it is no=
t entirely the trader=E2=80=99s fault. Amazingly, Citi also <em>programmed =
its computer system to confuse=C2=A0units and dollars</em>. The trader type=
d the order in the wrong box, but then the system calculated the notional v=
alue and showed it to the trader. If you multiply 58 million units by the $=
7,684 price of the basket, you get a $444 billion notional amount, which is=
 what the system should have shown, and which might have alerted the trader=
 that there was a problem. But the system instead displayed a notional amou=
nt of $58 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0the same as the number of units =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0which is exactly what the trader was expecting. Here is an insane par=
agraph from the FCA order (emphasis added):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Ordinarily, the Value at Benchmark field (ValAtBM) on the PTE =
screen displays the value of the relevant basket at a specified benchmark a=
nd is used where traders need to track the value against a reference price.=
 In this case, PTE defaulted to the option "Strike". The default "Strike" o=
ption was programmed to determine the price of the Index at the prior day's=
 close, by reference to an external data feed. <strong>However, as data fro=
m that external feed was unavailable, the price of the value of the Index i=
nstead defaulted to -1 rather than the benchmark price which was US$7684.40=
</strong>. The quantity of units was therefore multiplied by -1. There were=
 number of other fields on the PTE screen in which the total notional value=
 of the basket was correctly displayed. However, the trader only checked th=
e the ValAtBM on PTE to confirm the size of the basket. When the trader che=
cked the value of the inputted basket, they were presented with a figure of=
 negative 58 million for the value of the basket (58 million multiplied by =
-1). The trader saw a ValAtBM of -58,000,000, which was the number they exp=
ected to see, and thus they clicked Execute to continue to the next check. =
The quantity box, next to the ValAtBM also presented 58,000,000. Had the da=
ta feed been available, ValAtBM would have shown a basket of approximately =
US$444bn i.e., the true notional value of the basket.</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The most human possible mistake, in an order-entry =
system, is typing a dollar amount in the shares field.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> In designing an order-entry system, you should try to make it impossib=
le to make that mistake. But instead Citi=E2=80=99s system=C2=A0<em>default=
ed to displaying a value of $1 per share</em>=C2=A0(technically -$1, but th=
at=E2=80=99s a hard distinction to notice<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>) when its data feeds were turned off.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0So the trader typed 58,000,000 in the shares field, meaning to ty=
pe it in the dollars field, and the software was like =E2=80=9Cokay right 5=
8 million dollars.=E2=80=9D Insane!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, =
let=E2=80=99s call it=C2=A0human error. (=E2=80=9CThere were number of othe=
r fields on the PTE screen in which the total notional value of the basket =
was correctly displayed.=E2=80=9D) The next question=C2=A0is =E2=80=9Cwell =
what does the computer system do to safeguard against it?=E2=80=9D But you =
already know the answer. The answer is =E2=80=9Cthe computer system pops up=
 a series of warnings, but it does that on every trade, so traders have lea=
rned from experience to ignore the warnings.=E2=80=9D I mean, that is how I=
 interpret=C2=A0this passage from the FCA order:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">At 08:56 a =E2=80=98Trade Limit Warning=E2=80=99 pop-up a=
lert appeared within PTE. This presented the trader with 711 warning messag=
es, consisting of hard block and soft block messages, listed in a single al=
ert where only the first 18 lines of alerts were immediately visible unless=
 the person who received the alert scrolled down. The trader did not apprec=
iate their inputting error and overrode all of the soft warnings in the pop=
-up.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You get 711 alerts, you=
=C2=A0only see 18 of them, you are like =E2=80=9Cehh 18 alerts is pretty mu=
ch the normal number,=E2=80=9D you override them all without reading.</p><b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two hard blocks generated by the PTE=
 system, which could not be overridden, collectively stopped US$248bn of th=
e basket of equities progressing for execution. The trader was then present=
ed with a further pop-up alert entitled =E2=80=9CFinal Trade Confirmation=
=E2=80=9D. It contained a wave notional value of all the individual equitie=
s in the basket as a total (which was approximately US$196bn). The trader c=
licked the =E2=80=9COK=E2=80=9D option which routed the remaining basket of=
 equities with a notional value of $196bn into CitiSmart for execution usin=
g a VWAP trading algorithm, where individual parent and child orders were g=
enerated.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Okay here my sympath=
y starts to wane a little.=C2=A0Getting 711 warnings is apparently exactly =
as good as getting 18 warnings, and roughly as good as getting zero; nobody=
=E2=80=99s going to read 18 warnings. But getting one =E2=80=9Care you sure=
 you want to sell $196 billion of stock???=E2=80=9D pop-up=C2=A0<em>is=C2=
=A0</em>pretty informative? You probably=C2=A0<em>should=C2=A0</em>look at =
that one? And click yes if you want to sell $196 billion of stock? Which yo=
u don=E2=80=99t? Typing the number in the wrong box is understandable; conf=
irming a trade at 3,000 times the intended notional is worse. I suppose tha=
t if you have been doing this long enough you start to have a reflex like =
=E2=80=9CI typed my order on the screen already, I don=E2=80=99t need to re=
ad the confirmation pop-up before I click=C2=A0it,=E2=80=9D but here the so=
ftware design probably does know better than you do. You=C2=A0<em>should=C2=
=A0</em>read the confirmation pop-up before you click it!</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Now, it does seem to be important that this was a delta-one =
trader selling, not one stock, but rather a basket of 349 stocks. Citi <em>=
did</em> have=C2=A0various safeguards =E2=80=94=C2=A0what the FCA calls =E2=
=80=9Chard blocks=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0of the form =E2=80=9Cif someone t=
ries to send an order that is too big, don=E2=80=99t let them, even if they=
 click =E2=80=98yes.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D The problem is that these blocks app=
lied on a stock-by-stock basis, and this trader was selling all the stocks =
at once. Citi=E2=80=99s system had a hard block=C2=A0for =E2=80=9Corder not=
ional,=E2=80=9D which was =E2=80=9Cset at US$2bn (for each individual item =
in an order),=E2=80=9D so if you tried to sell more than $2 billion of a st=
ock the system would block it. It had a similar hard block for selling more=
 than 200 million=C2=A0<em>shares=C2=A0</em>of any stock.=C2=A0Selling $444=
 billion of a market-cap-weighted basket of 349 stocks will require selling=
 more than $2 billion of a lot of those stocks, and more than 200 million s=
hares of others, and those trades were blocked: =E2=80=9CThese hard blocks =
prevented 58 orders totalling US$248bn of the original US$444bn notional va=
lue of the basket progressing for execution.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">But that leaves orders to sell less than $2 billion each of 291 =
stocks, for a total of=C2=A0$196 billion, which is still a lot. And there w=
as no overall order-size hard block, what the FCA calls =E2=80=9Ca Wave Not=
ional hard block that would cancel basket trades that exceeded a total valu=
e limit and prevent the entire order progressing for execution.=E2=80=9D Th=
e FCA notes that Citi=E2=80=99s New York delta-one desk =E2=80=9Cdid have a=
 wave notional hard block of this type,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0set at $4 billion. Bu=
t =E2=80=9Cthe wave notional hard block was not rolled out to the EMEA inst=
ance of=E2=80=9D Citi=E2=80=99s software.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Citi knew that if traders were trying to=C2=A0sell more than $4 b=
illion of an index at once that was probably a mistake, but they only preve=
nted it=C2=A0in New York, not in London.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ot=
her protections also kicked in =E2=80=94=C2=A0including when the initial or=
ders caused the underlying stocks to drop =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the trader was=
 eventually able to cancel the rest of the order, but =E2=80=9Ca total US$1=
.4bn sell orders were executed across various European exchanges,=E2=80=9D =
causing a roughly 4% flash crash in European indexes=C2=A0and losing $48 mi=
llion for Citi.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, what were all th=
e risk managers doing? Some combination of =E2=80=9Cbeing on vacation,=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=9Calso ignoring annoying duplicative alerts,=E2=80=9D and =E2=
=80=9Csending emails to which they got no responses=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At 08:48 on 2 May 2022 as a result of schedu=
led staff leave, the Algorithmic Service Desk, a team responsible for real-=
time monitoring of internal executions, passed its responsibilities to the =
Electronic Execution desk (EE Desk). The EE Desk is primarily responsible f=
or real time monitoring of algorithmic order flow originated from external =
clients. The EE Desk did not escalate either the 284 information alerts gen=
erated from the erroneous basket trade, or the suspension alerts. Furthermo=
re, additional post-trade monitoring performed by the E-Trading Risk and Co=
ntrols Team (ETRC) failed to escalate the incident appropriately because th=
eir monitoring system filtered out all but eight of the information alerts =
relating to the erroneous basket trade. The ETRC team escalated the inciden=
t to the EE Desk covering the Algorithmic Service Desk, via email, at 09:31=
, 20 minutes after the trader had cancelled the order. Having received no r=
esponse to their email, the ETRC team followed up with them four hours late=
r.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Note the FCA=E2=80=99s time=
stamps. The Algorithmic Service Desk handed off its responsibilities at 8:4=
8; the trader was ignoring pop-up warnings by=C2=A08:56. I really do not kn=
ow what to make of the fact=C2=A0that the =E2=80=9Cteam responsible for rea=
l-time monitoring of internal executions=E2=80=9D went on vacation=C2=A0<em=
>eight minutes before=C2=A0</em>an internal execution got fat-fingered. Is =
some Citi trader fat-fingering trades like this all the time, and only the =
heroic concentration of the Algorithmic Service Desk keeps it from hourly d=
isaster?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I like to imagine that the Algorit=
hmic Service Desk person wrapped up work, sent an email formally handing of=
f her responsibilities, left her desk, and was still in the office waiting =
for the elevator when this all went down.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Her phone buzzed frantically and she took it out, looked, sighed,=
 turned it off,=C2=A0said =E2=80=9Cnope, I=E2=80=99m on vacation, this is=
=C2=A0someone else=E2=80=99s problem,=E2=80=9D and got on the elevator.</p>=
